Philippine Stocks: Philippine Bank of Communications, Republic

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n   a n d   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-05-30T04:29:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/metro-pacific-philippine-telephone-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 20.73, or 0.5
percent, to 4,295.24, its third day of gains.  Banco de Oro Unibank Inc. (BDO)  , the nation’s largest
bank, climbed 2.6 percent to 57.80 pesos, the sharpest gain
since May 17. The lender will pay 1 peso a share in dividend, a
stock exchange filing showed.  Philippine Bank of Communications (PBC)   tumbled 14
percent to 35 pesos, the lowest close since Oct. 29, after it
said Macquarie Group Ltd., an adviser to the lender’s
controlling shareholders, invited offers from “several banks”
to buy shares in the company for a minimum 25 pesos apiece.  Republic Cement Corp. (RCM)   jumped 10 percent to 6.16
pesos, the largest advance since Aug. 18, 2009. The company said
it will pay 28 centavos a share in special and regular
dividends. Republic Cement’s payout this year will exceed last
year’s dividend of 24 centavos a share and is the highest based
on data compiled by Bloomberg going back to 2007.  Universal Robina Corp. (URC)  , the nation’s second-
largest food and drinks company, increased 2.3 percent to 44
pesos, a fourth day of gains. Its 12-month share-price estimate
was raised by 23 percent to 50.30 pesos by Lovell Sarreal, an
analyst at ATR KimEng Securities Inc. The brokerage kept its
“buy” rating on the shares.  To contact the reporter on this story:
